Extract a reusable bounded-range analysis engine from AnalysisCoordinator. The runner executes the pipeline (spool -> features -> transcript -> detection) over a Range<TimeInterval> and writes durable stage frontiers. It does not know about playback state, tier policy, or scheduling.

WHY SEPARATE FROM COORDINATOR: The v1 design added preAnalyze() to AnalysisCoordinator, coupling background work to playback-only state. A dedicated runner gives a reusable core for preRollWarmup, playback hot-path, and future jobs.

INTERFACE:
  actor AnalysisJobRunner {
      private let store: AnalysisStore
      private let audioService: any AnalysisAudioProviding   // protocol from bd-1dl
      private let featureService: FeatureExtractionService
      private let transcriptEngine: TranscriptEngineService
      private let adDetectionService: any AdDetectionProviding // protocol from bd-1dl

      init(store: AnalysisStore, audioService: any AnalysisAudioProviding, featureService: FeatureExtractionService, transcriptEngine: TranscriptEngineService, adDetectionService: any AdDetectionProviding)

      func run(_ request: AnalysisRangeRequest) async -> AnalysisOutcome
  }

AnalysisRangeRequest (Playhead/Services/AnalysisJobRunner/AnalysisRangeRequest.swift):
  struct AnalysisRangeRequest: Sendable {
      enum Mode: Sendable { case preRollWarmup, playback, backgroundBackfill }
      let jobId: String
      let episodeId: String
      let podcastId: String
      let analysisAssetId: String
      let audioURL: URL
      let range: Range<TimeInterval>
      let mode: Mode
      let outputPolicy: OutputPolicy
      let priority: TaskPriority
  }

  enum OutputPolicy: Sendable {
      case writeWindowsAndCues    // pre-analysis: write AdWindows + materialize SkipCues
      case writeWindowsAndPushLive // playback: write AdWindows + push to live stream
      case writeWindowsOnly       // backfill: write AdWindows only
  }

AnalysisOutcome (Playhead/Services/AnalysisJobRunner/AnalysisOutcome.swift):
  struct AnalysisOutcome: Sendable {
      enum StopReason: Sendable {
          case reachedTarget
          case cancelledByPlayback
          case pausedForThermal
          case blockedByModel
          case memoryPressure
          case backgroundExpired
          case failed(String)
      }
      let assetId: String
      let requestedCoverageSec: Double
      let featureCoverageSec: Double
      let transcriptCoverageSec: Double
      let cueCoverageSec: Double
      let newCueCount: Int
      let stopReason: StopReason
  }

IMPLEMENTATION (in AnalysisJobRunner.run()):

  func run(_ request: AnalysisRangeRequest) async -> AnalysisOutcome {
      // 1. Resolve or create AnalysisAsset + AnalysisSession via store
      // 2. Register for memory warnings
      var receivedMemoryWarning = false
      let memoryObserver = NotificationCenter.default.addObserver(
          forName: UIApplication.didReceiveMemoryWarningNotification,
          object: nil, queue: nil
      ) { _ in receivedMemoryWarning = true }
      defer { NotificationCenter.default.removeObserver(memoryObserver) }

      // Pipeline stages with thermal/memory/cancellation checks between each:
      // Stage 1: Decode audio shards
      let shards = try await audioService.decodeShards(audioURL: request.audioURL, range: request.range)
      if Task.isCancelled { return checkpointAndReturn(.cancelledByPlayback, ...) }
      if ProcessInfo.processInfo.thermalState.rawValue >= ProcessInfo.ThermalState.serious.rawValue {
          return checkpointAndReturn(.pausedForThermal, ...)
      }
      if receivedMemoryWarning { return checkpointAndReturn(.memoryPressure, ...) }

      // Stage 2: Feature extraction
      // ... (same pattern: do work, check guards)

      // Stage 3: Transcription
      // ... (same pattern)

      // Stage 4: Ad detection
      let adWindows = try await adDetectionService.detect(...)
      // ... check guards

      // Stage 5: Materialize cues (conditional on outputPolicy)
      if request.outputPolicy == .writeWindowsAndCues {
          let materializer = SkipCueMaterializer(store: store)
          let newCount = try await materializer.materialize(adWindows: adWindows, analysisAssetId: request.analysisAssetId, source: "preAnalysis")
          // ... update cueCoverageSec
      }

      // Stage 6: Checkpoint final progress
      try await store.updateJobProgress(jobId: request.jobId, ...)

      return AnalysisOutcome(stopReason: .reachedTarget, ...)
  }

  private func checkpointAndReturn(_ reason: AnalysisOutcome.StopReason, ...) -> AnalysisOutcome {
      // Persist current frontier to store, then return outcome
  }

PLATFORM CORRECTION -- THERMAL CHECK BETWEEN STAGES: The runner MUST poll ProcessInfo.processInfo.thermalState between each pipeline stage. If thermalState >= .serious, checkpoint partial progress and return .pausedForThermal. Polling thermalState is cheap (reads a cached ProcessInfo value). ProcessInfo.thermalStateDidChangeNotification can supplement but must not be the sole mechanism.

PLATFORM CORRECTION -- MEMORY PRESSURE: Register for UIApplication.didReceiveMemoryWarningNotification at start of run() and deregister on completion. Between stages, check if warning was received. Feature extraction and transcription allocate large audio buffers and model tensors; continuing under memory pressure risks jetsam.

QoS: .utility for preRollWarmup and backgroundBackfill, .userInitiated for playback. Set via Task.currentPriority or by running pipeline stages with the request's priority.

Cancellation: checks Task.isCancelled between stages. On cancellation, checkpoints partial progress and returns .cancelledByPlayback.

